  "What is a radical?": "",
  "An expression that uses a root symbol (√) to indicate a root of a number": "",
  "Any expression with an exponent": "",
  "A fraction with variables": "",
  "A number that is always irrational": "",
  "A radical is a mathematical expression that uses a root symbol (√) to indicate a root of a number. The most common radical is the square root, but cube roots and higher roots are also radicals.": "",
  "What is a radicand?": "",
  "The number or expression under the radical symbol": "",
  "The answer after simplifying a radical": "",
  "The small number written above the radical": "",
  "The coefficient in front of the radical": "",
  "The radicand is the number or expression inside the radical symbol. For example, in √50, the radicand is 50. Simplifying means extracting perfect square factors from the radicand.": "",
  "What is a perfect square?": "",
  "A number divisible by 4": "",
  "A number whose square root is a whole number": "",
  "A number with exactly two factors": "",
  "Any even number": "",
  "A perfect square is a number that is the square of a whole number, such as 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, 81, 100. Its square root is an integer.": "",
  "What does 'simplest radical form' mean?": "",
  "The radicand is a prime number": "",
  "The radical equals a whole number": "",
  "No perfect square factors remain under the radical and no radicals appear in any denominator": "",
  "The radical has been converted to a decimal": "",
  "A radical is in simplest form when the radicand has no perfect square factors (other than 1) and there are no radicals in any denominator. Both conditions must be satisfied.": "",
  "What does 'rationalize the denominator' mean?": "",
  "Move the radical from the denominator to the numerator": "",
  "Remove the radical from the denominator by multiplying numerator and denominator by an appropriate radical": "",
  "Simplify the numerator only": "",
  "Convert the fraction to a decimal": "",
  "Rationalizing the denominator means eliminating any radical from the denominator of a fraction by multiplying both the numerator and denominator by the appropriate radical expression.": "",
  "What is the product property of radicals?": "",
